  "opinion": "As a fitness trainer in Kansas City who’s seen the physical and mental toll of stress firsthand, I’ve noticed how stereotype threat—where people internalize negative expectations about their group—can quietly undermine potential in fields like STEM. For instance, when a high school student from a marginalized background hears that 'girls aren’t good at math,' it doesn’t just affect their confidence; it can make them avoid challenging problems altogether. This isn’t just a theoretical issue—it’s real and deeply personal. From my experience working with clients, I’ve seen how stress can manifest as fatigue, anxiety, or even physical tension, which are all symptoms of stereotype threat. The good news is, addressing this isn’t about fixing people—it’s about creating environments where everyone feels safe to try. In my gym, we emphasize progress over perfection, and I’ve started incorporating mindfulness practices to help clients manage anxiety. Similarly, in STEM education, we should shift from a 'one-size-fits-all' approach to personalized support that acknowledges individual fears. Schools could implement mentorship programs where students from underrepresented groups work alongside peers in STEM, fostering connections that counteract isolation. It’s crucial to normalize conversations about bias without shaming individuals. As someone who grew up with parents who both have advanced degrees, I know how powerful role models can be. By highlighting diverse role models in STEM and making classrooms inclusive, we can help students see themselves in the field. Ultimately, addressing stereotype threat requires empathy, not just data—it’s about building bridges where every person feels they belong.",
